1. d4
{ Welcome to the final part of my Lifetime 1.d4 Repertoire! In Part 1, @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/course/47519/@@LinkEnd@@, I covered all of Black's sidelines, in Part 2 @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/course/53465/@@LinkEnd@@, I covered the Indian Games with 1. d4 Nf6, and now finally we have reached the toughest part of all, covering the Queen's Gambit with 1. d4 d5.   Much like we saw in the first two parts, my goal is to fight for a strategic edge such as space advantage, a better structure, or the bishop pair, and this is not really a repertoire aimed at tearing Black's head off. But, given that Black has placed a pawn in the center on the very first move of the game, I find it harder to accomplish these goals, and I was actually surprised to find that even in some very solid variations, White ended up with some kind of attacking chances.   While I believe that part 3 is more demanding than parts 1 and 2 in how difficult playing the resulting positions will be, I still am very happy with the analysis I did and I think I managed to pose Black a lot of problems in some very solid variations. The lines given in this file are all covered in the course. Happy Studying! }
1... d5 { 1...Nf6  This move was the subject of part 2. } 2. c4 e6
{ 2...c6  3.Nc3  If White is happy to play into the Meran, this move order does a very good job of cutting down on some of Black's extra options.  3...Nf6  4.e3  And here in addition to e6, transposing to the Semi-Slav, I covered Black's other 3 main tries.  4...g6   4...a6   4...Bf5   2...dxc4  3.e3  Nf6   3...e5  4.Bxc4  a6  5.Nf3  e6  6.O-O  Now, I covered the dubious but still reasonably common 6...b5 as well as the main move 6...c5.  6...c5   6...b5 }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ This is the main move, but I covered all of Black's other tries as well.   3...c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3+=  I did not discover any groundbreaking new ideas against the Tarrasch, but luckily the existing state of the theory was very nice for White.   3...a6  4.Bg5!  I like this move, which seems to secure White a small edge. }
4. Nc3 c6
{ 4...a6  5.c5!  I think this is a great way to steer the game into an uncomfortable position for Black.   4...Bb4  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  I ended up choosing the old mainline against the Ragozin, which surprisingly is out of fashion nowadays. I don't think Black is equalizing too easily here.   4...dxc4  5.e4  Bb4  6.Bxc4  I advocate this enterprising pawn sacrifice against the Vienna, but with an important novelty early on in the mainline that I think poses Black some problems.   4...c5  The Semi-Tarrasch was quite a challenge as well. I ended up going for the mainline with  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  Nxc3  7.bxc3  Some long lines seem more or less okay for Black, but I'm satisfied that I found a new idea which should pose serious problems for a human to solve, and at the end leads to a position that feels more comfortable for White to me even if the computer calls it equal.   4...h6  This move has curiously gained some popularity in recent years. I have no idea why, but I found a comfortable way for White to play.   4...Nbd7  5.Bf4   4...Be7  The proper Queen's Gambit Declined is one of Black's most solid options against 1.d4 in the history of chess. I think I managed to put him under some pressure after 5.Bf4. }
5. e3
{ It was a bit awkward to propose a recommendation against the Semi-Slav, both because I believe it is Black's best opening against 1.d4 and because I already wrote a course on it from Black's point of view @@StartBracket@@ @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/lifetime-repertoires-semi-slav/course/31529/@@LinkEnd@@ @@EndBracket@@ and had to fight against my own analysis. I ended up choosing the Meran, and I thought I found a position that felt a bit more comfortable from the White-side, but in a higher chess sense, should be more or less fine for Black. This is the normal result when analyzing a mainline and trying hard to find an edge with White. }
