5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Of course this is the move. Black trades off a pair of minor pieces since he has less space. }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4
{ Nowadays, almost every game continues with Nb8-d7, which is undoubtedly the best move, though it has to be mentioned that Nb8-c6 enjoyed some popularity once upon a time. }
11... Nd7 12. O-O b6
{ This is a better moment to play b7-b6 as Black need not fear d4-d5 just yet. I consider this the starting position of the modern Semi-Tarrasch. }
13. Rad1 Bb7 14. Rfe1 Rc8 { This is played approximately 100% of the time. }
15. Bb3
{ Now, Black has a few options. It's very important to understand what White is trying to accomplish, and how Black can try to stop him. I think White's best coordination is to play Re1-e3 and Qd2-e2, and if he can safely pull this off, he will be better. Black's queenside pawns will be stuck, and White will have secured the e4-pawn as well as the c2 and c3 squares, severely limiting any hope for queenside counterplay. Additionally, the pieces will be very well placed for a d4-d5 sacrifice with e5-e6 to follow. Black should take care not to let this happen. Alternatively, if White can play d4-d5 and get his pawn all the way to d6 without any hiccups along the way, he will be much better. Black must be careful to prevent this as well. }
15... Re8
{ First thing's first. Black plays some prophylaxis against d4-d5. Now, White would love to go for Re1-e3 followed by Qd2-e2, but he is not quite able to pull this off just yet. }
16. h3
{ This move is subtle but very strong. White wants Re1-e3 and Qd2-e2 next without walking into Nf6-g4. }
16... Nf6
{ This move is very necessary. Black attacks the e4-pawn directly to prevent White from reaching the best coordination with Re1-e3 and Qd2-e2. }
17. Qf4
{ Now, once more, Black should be very direct. If White is allowed to play Nf3-e5, he will freeze the knight on f6 as f7 will become weak, and g4-g5 is not messing around. }
17... Nh5
{ Black kicks White's queen, questioning her stability before returning to f6 next. }
18. Qh2 { This is a sad square for the queen, but she will not stay for long. }
18... h6
{ This is certainly best and has been consistently the choice of Ding Liren as well as all correspondence players. Black is under a lot of pressure but his position seems to be more or less holding together. }
19. d5
{ I like executing the typical pawn sacrifice, but with an important twist. }
19... exd5 20. Ba4
{ This was my best attempt to cause some trouble for one of the more vexing openings White can bash his head against the wall. White provokes Black's rook onto an inferior square. }
20... Bc6 21. Bxc6 Rxc6 22. Rxd5 { White wins a piece, and the game. } *

