{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted is one of Black's most solid defenses against 1.d4. It doesn't really offer him many counter chances, and as such has never been wildly popular, but breaking it down is anything but straightforward, and a lot of strong guys have used it in recent years when they are looking to be as solid as possible and are quite happy to make a draw with Black. It took me a lot of effort to find a variation I liked, but I ultimately was satisfied with what I found. }
3. e3
{ White can also consider Ng1-f3, but this gives Black some annoying additional options such as a quick Bc8-g4 or even  3...a6  . This move strikes me as simpler. Black normally lets the pawn go with Ng8-f6 but he has tried some other things as well. }
3... e5
{ If Black is hell-bent on not entering the mainlines, this is his best option, but it will not equalize. }
4. Bxc4 Nc6
{ In recent years, Black has often looked to delay the capture on d4. I don't really see a point. }
5. Nf3 { White falls for Black's supposed trap. } 5... exd4 6. exd4
{ This leaves Black in a lousy version of the mainline as he will not even get his bishop to d6. }
6... Nf6 7. O-O
{ White's rook is coming to e1, meaning that Black will be forced to put his bishop on e7 rather than d6. After something like }
7... Be7 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3
{ White has a clear plan of action for all of his pieces with Nb1-c3, Bc1-f4, and eventually Nf3-e5. I can't see anything sensible for Black to do or any way for him to show any play against the isolani. }
