{ This position is perhaps the most topical one in the entirety of 1.d4 openings. Broadly speaking, White should be better if he can develop his c1-bishop outside of the pawn chain and then play e2-e3 next without anything bad happening to him in the meantime, and if Black lets this happen, he usually ends up a bit worse. Black's main moves here are certainly c6, c5, Bb4, dxc4, and Be7. But, it is important to be ready for his side attempts as well. }
4... Nbd7
{ Of Black's available fourth move sidelines, I think this one is his best option. But I also don't think he will equalize so easily. }
5. Bf4 dxc4 { The main move by far. } 6. e3 b5
{ This is definitely Black's best option. He is certainly not going to equalize, but he may be able to reach a defensible position. }
7. Nxb5 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Nd5 9. a3 Nxc3 10. Qd2
{ Black will soon lose his piece back. The position simplifies a lot in the coming moves, but White retains better chances. }
10... Nd5 11. axb4 { Now things get pretty forcing. } 11... Nxf4 12. exf4 Bb7
13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Nb6 15. Ne5 Qd6
{ This position has been reached a bunch of times. Black will lose his c4-pawn, but he contends that the position has a high likelihood of simplifying thanks to all of the isolated pawns for both sides and that he will hope to get a holdable rook endgame one pawn down. If you dig deep enough, I think this may be possible for him, but in practice, it feels so miserable to play chess like this. }
16. Rfd1
{ White is ready for Ra5-c5 next, and the c4-pawn will fall. Black has reasonable saving chances but I could never understand why anyone would voluntarily go for such a position. }
