{ Obviously White is not thrilled about losing a tempo to play this move, but it was a necessary loss as if he had placed the bishop on d3 in one move,   10...e5  would have come at a moment when White would not have been well equipped to deal with it. This position has been reached a lot of times with White to move @@StartBracket@@Black will have had to have played badly for that to happen of course@@EndBracket@@ when he is clearly better, but even a tempo down I think he has chances to fight for an edge. In general, White's best plan is to place a rook on the d-file and then fight for e3-e4. Normally, he would do this with Qd1-c2 and Rad1, but I quite like leaving the queen on d1 and going for Ra1-c1-c2-d2. The queen can be a bit of a target on c2 once the c-file opens. Some key points. First off, it is absolutely critical to not ever let Black play  10...dxc4  and then be able to comfortably meet  11.bxc4  with  11...c5  . You need to always be ready with d4-d5 in response. Similarly, White really does not want to allow Black to play c7-c5 and then take back with the knight on d5. Both of these goals can be accomplished with accurate play. }
