{ 14...Qf5!  According to the machine, this was the way. It looks like a very scary move as after  15.Qe2  Black is hard pressed to deal with Bb3-c2, but after  15...Qa5!  The computer just barely manages to hang on. White can execute one of his key breaks though.  16.d5!?  exd5  17.Qh5  h6  18.Nxd5!  I can easily imagine Adams taking one look at this position and telling himself 'No way.' It looks like Black should be crushed on the kingside in just a couple of moves.  18...Nxd5  19.Rxd5  Bxd5  20.Nxf7  c6!  The machine only sees a perpetual for White. }
15. Nge4 Qf5 { 15...Bxe4  16.Nxe4  d5 is coming next all the same. } 16. d5
{ Adams understandably did not want to blunt his own light squared bishop with c7-c6 early on, but now White gets through one of his big breaks. He still has a lead in development thanks to Black spending a lot of time on Nf6-d5-xf4, and that persists deep into the endgame. }
16... exd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Rxd5 Rfd8 21. Rc1
{ Black is somewhat paralyzed. The bishop on d6 is vulnerable, but can't move. }
21... Rac8 22. Rc3 Be7 23. Rxd8+ Bxd8 24. f5
{ Using a pretty tactic, White gains more space on the kingside. Black's position is dreadfully passive. }
24... Kg7
{ 24...c6  This offered more saving chances, but I still would not want to be Black after  25.f6 }
25. Nd6 { Well spotted. } 25... Rb8 26. Ne8+ Kf8 27. fxg6
{ A clever in-between move. } 27... hxg6
{ 27...Kxe8?  28.g7  White makes a queen. } 28. Nxc7
{ The dust has settled, and White is a pawn up. His advantage in activity that was gained early on has been converted into something tangible, and Gelfand did manage to convert the resulting endgame. }
